FFH happened. It was fun but left much to be desired story wise. That being said, Mysterio’s “last words” were a chilling warning to Peter- the real world is nothing like our childhood dreams
We start with a kid who loves the avengers and superheroism. Wasn’t that all of us, as kids? Tom’s Peter is that metaphor- to hold on to the dreams of hope as we get older and become adults.

Then Tom realizes the brutality of that world (likely through Ben’s death in the Avengers battle from A1) and realizes he wants to make a difference, to protect the “little guy” like his uncle was. To be a hero for folks that the avengers don’t really interact with.

He joins the avengers, and realizes that he can’t stay true to his self (the entire point of homecoming). So he leaves to help the “little guys” like vulture… and folks like Ben and aunt may, Ned, etc

And the MCU has a much better understanding of Spider-Man/Peter than the current editors at Marvel Comics. 🏃

So my point? MCU’s Spider-Man is a worthy adaptation of the comics. Because he’s GROWING and having all those life lessons at the START of his journey, does not make sense. It may not be entirely comic accurate, but it nails who Peter is as a person.

Peter loses everything in NWH but still persists as Spider-Man because he’s not a “god that takes”, like Osborn. He’s a man that “looks out for the little guy.” Because “that’s what we do.” NWH was a ideological study of Spider-Man’s motivations and ethics, and it did brilliantly
